One Hundred Ninth Ave. (Hawtree Creek Road, Suwanee Ave.), at the N.W. corner of Pinegrove Street, showing in a set of four views the J.F. Disbrow house of 1860 to 1873. It was later purchased by one Greenwood. John W. Greenwood of the same family purchased land here in 1834 from James Ditmas. One Bonk was the owner in 1934. He moved the house from this site. View No. 4 shows the barn in the rear of the house.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

One Hundred Ninth Ave. (Suwanee Ave.), at the N.W. corner of Pinegrove Street (formerly Allen Street), showing the Greenwood house. In 1909 this property contained 20 acres and belonged to A. Van Sicklen. Note: that if locating under old location, it would be Lincoln Ave., south side, opposite Allen Street. The house was still standing in 1931.

About 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

108-16 Pinegrove Street, at the N.W. corner of 109th Avenue, showing two rear views of a Van Sicklen house, said to be about two hundred years old.
